<subSubSection id="C36B655FF93A142EFF72F906FE278B7E" pageId="2" pageNumber="298" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BCE36D4F93A142EFF72F906FE278B7E" blockId="2.[122,762,1327,1831]" pageId="2" pageNumber="298">
<emphasis id="B905EAC6F93A142EFF72F906FED18A9E" bold="true" box="[148,279,1711,1735]" pageId="2" pageNumber="298">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin “two-arms”, a name reflecting the two prominent arms. The Latin “brachium” is of common gender, but shall be treated as feminine, in accordance with ICZN article 30.1.4.2.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
